.SH NAME
CanvasRenderingContext2D.shadowBlur \- CanvasRenderingContext2D:
shadowBlur property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]CanvasRenderingContext2D.shadowBlur\f[B]\f[R] property of
the Canvas 2D API specifies the amount of blur applied to shadows.
The default is \f[CR]0\f[R] (no blur).
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Shadows are only drawn if the \f[CR]shadowColor\f[R]
property is set to a non\-transparent value.
One of the \f[CR]shadowBlur\f[R], \f[CR]shadowOffsetX\f[R], or
\f[CR]shadowOffsetY\f[R] properties must be non\-zero, as well.
.RE
.SH VALUE
A non\-negative float specifying the level of shadow blur, where
\f[CR]0\f[R] represents no blur and larger numbers represent
increasingly more blur.
This value doesn\[cq]t correspond to a number of pixels, and is not
affected by the current transformation matrix.
The default value is \f[CR]0\f[R].
Negative, \f[CR]Infinity\f[R], and \f[CR]NaN\f[R] values are ignored.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Adding a shadow to a shape
This example adds a blurred shadow to a rectangle.
The \f[CR]shadowColor\f[R] property sets its color, and
\f[CR]shadowBlur\f[R] sets its level of blurriness.
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]canvas\f[R] id=\[dq]canvas\[dq]></\f[B]canvas\f[R]>
.EE
.SS JavaScript
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] canvas = document.getElementById(\[dq]canvas\[dq]);
\f[B]const\f[R] ctx = canvas.getContext(\[dq]2d\[dq]);

\f[I]// Shadow\f[R]
ctx.shadowColor = \[dq]red\[dq];
ctx.shadowBlur = 15;

\f[I]// Rectangle\f[R]
ctx.fillStyle = \[dq]blue\[dq];
ctx.fillRect(20, 20, 150, 100);
.EE
.SS Result
.SS WebKit/Blink\-specific notes
In WebKit\- and Blink\-based browsers, the non\-standard and deprecated
method \f[CR]ctx.setShadow()\f[R] is implemented besides this property.
.IP
.EX
